trans-unit.source: App Model v2.0 | Microsoft Azure
trans-unit.target: App Model v2.0 | Microsoft Azure

trans-unit.source: How to build a .NET native app that signs users in with both personal Microsoft Account and work or school accounts.
trans-unit.target: How to build a .NET native app that signs users in with both personal Microsoft Account and work or school accounts.

trans-unit.source: With the v2.0 app model, you can quickly add authentication to your desktop apps with support for both personal Microsoft accounts and work or school accounts.
trans-unit.target: With the v2.0 app model, you can quickly add authentication to your desktop apps with support for both personal Microsoft accounts and work or school accounts.

trans-unit.source: It also enables your app to securely communicate with a backend web api, as well as a few of the <linkText>Office 365 Unified APIs</linkText><title></title>.
trans-unit.target: It also enables your app to securely communicate with a backend web api, as well as a few of the <linkText>Office 365 Unified APIs</linkText><title></title>.

trans-unit.source: This information applies to the v2.0 app model public preview.
trans-unit.target: This information applies to the v2.0 app model public preview.

trans-unit.source: For instructions on how to integrate with the generally available Azure AD service, please refer to the <linkText>Azure Active Directory Developer Guide</linkText><title></title>.
trans-unit.target: For instructions on how to integrate with the generally available Azure AD service, please refer to the <linkText>Azure Active Directory Developer Guide</linkText><title></title>.

trans-unit.source: For <linkText>.NET native apps that run on a device</linkText><title></title>, Azure AD provides the Active Directory Authentication Library, or ADAL.
trans-unit.target: For <linkText>.NET native apps that run on a device</linkText><title></title>, Azure AD provides the Active Directory Authentication Library, or ADAL.

trans-unit.source: ADAL's sole purpose in life is to make it easy for your app to get tokens for calling web services.
trans-unit.target: ADAL's sole purpose in life is to make it easy for your app to get tokens for calling web services.

trans-unit.source: If the user successfully signs-in, ADAL will receive and cache a token for you, and you can proceed to call the GetTodoList() method with confidence.

trans-unit.source: Congratulations! You now have a working .NET WPF app that has the ability to authenticate users & securely call Web APIs using OAuth 2.0. Run your both projects, and sign in with either a personal Microsoft account or a work or school account. Add tasks to that user's To-Do list. Sign out, and sign back in as another user to view their To-Do list. Close the app, and re-run it. Notice how the user's session remains intact - that is becuase the app caches tokens in a local file.
trans-unit.target: Congratulations! You now have a working .NET WPF app that has the ability to authenticate users & securely call Web APIs using OAuth 2.0. Run your both projects, and sign in with either a personal Microsoft account or a work or school account. Add tasks to that user's To-Do list. Sign out, and sign back in as another user to view their To-Do list. Close the app, and re-run it. Notice how the user's session remains intact - that is becuase the app caches tokens in a local file.

trans-unit.source: ADAL makes it easy to incorporate common identity features into your app, using both personal and work accounts.
trans-unit.target: ADAL makes it easy to incorporate common identity features into your app, using both personal and work accounts.

trans-unit.source: It takes care of all the dirty work for you - cache management, OAuth protocol support, presenting the user with a login UI, refreshing expired tokens, and more.
trans-unit.target: It takes care of all the dirty work for you - cache management, OAuth protocol support, presenting the user with a login UI, refreshing expired tokens, and more.

trans-unit.source: All you really need to know is a single API call, authContext.AcquireTokenAsync(...).
trans-unit.target: All you really need to know is a single API call, authContext.AcquireTokenAsync(...).
